sed","1325":"1325","<1292>":"1292","<1318>":"1318","1294":"1294","1292":"1292","1318":"1318","Of, Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England":"Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Accot,Devonshire,England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Giffard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: (i) relationship name from the Continental Germanic personal name  <i>Gifard</i>. (ii) nickname, perhaps sometimes from Old French  <i>giffard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."],"variants":[{"name":"Jeffords","meanings":["English: variant of   Gifford  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Jefford","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]},{"name":"Guiver","meanings":["English: (i) nickname, apparently from Middle English  <i>giver</i> ‘giver, donor, bestower’. (ii) variant of   Giffard   with voicing of /f/ to /v/ and loss of final  <i>-d</i>."]},{"name":"Gafford","meanings":["English (southeastern): assimilated form of <b>Gatford</b>, a name of various origins. In Sussex and Surrey it is perhaps a variant of the habitational name <b>Catford</b> from a place so called in Somerset. <b>Gatford</b> is also from the habitational names Gateford (in Worksop, Nottinghamshire) or Gateforth (near Selby, Yorkshire), both formed with Old English <i>gāt</i> ‘goat’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, influenced by Old Norse <i>geit</i> ‘goat’.","Probably also an altered form of German <b>Gaffert</b>: habitational name from Gaffert near Köslin, Brandenburg, or from a personal name formed with Middle High German <i>gate</i> ‘fellow, companion’. The surname <i>Gaffert</i> is very rare in Germany.","English: perhaps an altered form of   Gatewood  , an occupational name for a ‘goatherd’ (Middle English <i>gate-werde</i>, Old English <i>gātweard</i>) or for a ‘gate keeper’ (Middle English <i>gateward</i>, Old English <i>ʒeatweard</i>, dialect <i>gātward</i>)."]},{"name":"Gifford","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Giffard</b>, either from the Middle English personal name <i>Gifard</i>, derived from an Old French name of this form deriving from ancient Germanic <i>geb-</i> ‘give, gift’ + <i>hard-</i> ‘hardy, brave’, or perhaps sometimes a nickname from Old French <i>gif(f)ard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."]},{"name":"Jefferd","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]}]},{"name":"Osbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ōs</i> ‘god’ + <i>beorht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It is not now common, but in the earlier 20th century it enjoyed a modest vogue in Britain, being borne for example by the cartoonist  Osbert Lancaster  (  1908–86 ) and the writer  Osbert Sitwell  (  1892–1969 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Osbert Giffard was born in 1292, in Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Beatrice Murdac. He died in Devon, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"<1292>–":"1292–Surnud","1294–Female":"1294–Surnud","1318–1325":"1318–1325","1292–Male":"1292–Surnud","1325":"1325","<1292>":"1292","<1318>":"1318","1294":"1294","1292":"1292","1318":"1318","Of, Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England":"Twyford, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Accot,Devonshire,England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"<1292>–":"1292–Kuollut","1294–Female":"1294–Kuollut","1318–1325":"1318–1325","1292–Male":"1292–Kuollut","1325":"1325","<1292>":"1292","<1318>":"1318","1294":"1294","1292":"1292","1318":"1318","Of, Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England":"Twyford, Buckinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Accot,Devonshire,England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"<1292>–":"1292–Décédé","1294–Female":"1294–Décédée","1318–1325":"1318–1325","1292–Male":"1292–Décédé","1325":"1325","<1292>":"1292","